hands_on_practices.solution:
We model the photon’s path as a 3D random walk with step-length distribution 
$$p(s)=\ell^{-1}e^{-s/\ell}\,. $$
1. Compute moments of $s$:
$$\langle s\rangle=\int_0^\infty s\,p(s)\,ds=\ell,\qquad
\langle s^2\rangle=\int_0^\infty s^2\,p(s)\,ds=2\ell^2\,. $$
2. After $N$ scatterings, the mean squared displacement is
$$\langle r^2\rangle=N\langle s^2\rangle=2N\ell^2\,. $$
Each step takes on average time $\langle t\rangle=\langle s\rangle/c=\ell/c$, so the diffusion coefficient is
$$D=\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{\langle r^2\rangle}{6t}
=\frac{\langle s^2\rangle}{6\langle t\rangle}
=\frac{2\ell^2}{6(\ell/c)}=\frac{\ell c}{3}\,. $$
3. The mean escape time $T(r)$ in a sphere of radius $R$ satisfies 
$$D\nabla^2T=-1,\quad T(R)=0\,. $$
In spherical symmetry 
$$\frac1{r^2}\frac{d}{dr}\!\Bigl(r^2\frac{dT}{dr}\Bigr)=-\frac1D
\;\Longrightarrow\;
T(r)=-\frac{r^2}{6D}+C\,, $$
and $T(R)=0$ gives $C=R^2/(6D)$, so 
$$T(0)=\frac{R^2}{6D}\,. $$
4. The average number of scatterings is 
$$N=\frac{T(0)}{\langle t\rangle}
=\frac{R^2/(6D)}{\ell/c}
=\frac{R^2c}{6D\,\ell}
=\frac{R^2c}{6(\ell c/3)\,\ell}
=\frac{R^2}{2\ell^2}
=\frac{\tau^2}{2}\,. $$
